    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-03T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-03T02:00:00-05:00" n="5"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d5">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/1–346: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Robertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-03T14:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 3, 1946—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 3—11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Personal to Secretary of State from Marshall. My message 18 of December
                        26<note n="19" xml:id="d5fn19">
                        <ref target="frus1945v07#pg_813">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1945, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>, p. 813</ref>.</note> requesting your
                    personal estimate of the Soviet intent in Manchuria and relations between Russia
                    and the Chinese Communists evidently did not reach you in Russia. I also raised
                    the question as to whether the difficulties the Generalissimo reports in his
                    relations with Russia in Manchuria are not mostly of the same pattern as our own
                    similar difficulties in Europe, or whether Soviet policy in Manchuria is
                    deliberately calculated to mitigate against an effective and unified China.</p>
                <p>Your personal views on the above for eye only and to be kept out of the records
                    would be most helpful to me in the present status of my negotiations with the
                    Chinese. [Marshall.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
